    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "I see. So it's basically about catching laws that are fundamentally wrong even if the government followed all the right steps to pass them. Does that mean the \"procedural\" side of things is less important for ensuring real justice when it comes to fundamental rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The procedural side of due process is crucial for ensuring that the government doesn't trample on fundamental rights, but when it comes to substantive rights, the Constitution's text and history take precedence. In cases where a law is fundamentally at odds with the Constitution, the procedural rules are secondary to the underlying principle of protecting individual liberties. The Founding Fathers intended for the Constitution to be a living document that evolves with the nation, and substantive due process allows judges to interpret that intent and protect fundamental rights even if the government followed proper procedures.",
